The compressible Navier–Stokes–Korteweg equation (
					1.1) can govern the motion of compressible fluids such as liquid vapor mixtures, which is the compressible fluids endowed with internal capillarity. Capillary phenomena are ubiquitous, complex and diverse in nature and they are also found in various industrial processes that ranging from off-shore engineering to automotive (e.g., carburant injection) and chemical engineering. The formulation of the theory of capillary with diffusive interface can be traced back to the work of Van de Waals [
					51] and Korteweg [
					29] more than one century ago, and was actually derived in its modern form in the 1980s using the second gradient theory, see for instance [
					11]. Heida and Málek [
					19] also derived (
					1.1) by the entropy production method which does not require to introduce any new or non-standard concepts such as multipolarity or interstitial working which are used in [
					11]. One can see easily that when




									κ
									=
									0


							\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa =0$$\end{document}


					, system (
					1.1) is reduced to the classical Navier–Stokes equations for compressible fluids.

In recent years, there have been a great number of mathematical studies on the compressible Naviver-Stokes-Korteweg equations. In what follows, let us first focus on the large-time behavior of solutions to the isentropic compressible Navier–Stokes–Korteweg equations, which is related to our interest. When the initial perturbation of the non-vacuum constant states is small, Wang and Tan [
					52], Tan et al. [
					49], and Tan and Wang [
					48] established the optimal time decay rates of the global classical/strong solutions for the isentropic compressible Navier–Stokes–Korteweg equations. Tan and Zhang [
					50] further obtained the time decay rates of more derivatives of solutions when the initial perturbation is in the negative Sobolev





